6 of the last 10 home teams have won the NFC championship. 49ers are the home team.

As a Packers Fan this hurts me to say but the Packers have been incredibly inconsistent throughout the season. Both offense and defense have struggled but by some strategy and coming out strong against the Seahawks have made it through. The Packers rely too heavily on Aaron Rodgers and even this season he has been struggling to find and connect with receivers. The 49ers are a very strong team all around and the Packers lost to them this season already. Being an away game for the Packers hasn't been positive for them in the past and is only positive for the 49ers.

There are only two teams left at this time, Green Bay and San Francisco. Green Bay had mixed levels of play throughout the season, including a dreadful loss to the 49ers during the season and nearly letting Seattle comeback in the divisional round. San Francisco, when healthy, has been the most dominant team in the NFC with big wins over Green Bay, Seattle in Week 17 and Minnesota in the divisional round. San Francisco is playing at home in the matchup and should have favorable matchups across the board.

1. Saints and Eagles are already eliminated. 2. 49ers are -7 spread against Vikings, which translates roughly into 75% odds of winning. 3. Packers are -4.5 spread against Seahawks, which translates roughly into 67% odds of winning. 4. There aren't any point spreads available for the NFC championship game since the teams aren't decided yet, but here are the odds of winning I came up with based on home field advantage, seed, season record, and my own personal bias against the Redskins (who Kirk Cousins used to play for): 49ers over Packers, 58%; 49ers over Seahawks, 68%; Packers over Vikings, 63%; Seahawks over Vikings, 55%. Upsets are obviously the obverse of these %s. 5. I created a spreadsheet that calculates the 8 possible paths these three remaining games could take and created the percentages forecasted above.
